Add the delegate series of functions

These functions allow void functions that would usually block the UI
thread to run in a separate thread. They are accompanied by a series of
macros that easily turn any given void function (with 0 to 3 arguments)
into a function that runs in the aforementioned thread.

For example, consider the following function:

```c
void f(const char *name)
{
    printf("Hello %s!\n", name);
    sleep(10);
}
```

Applying the macros produces:

```c
DELEGATE_1(f, const char *, name)
{
    printf("Hello %s!\n", name);
    sleep(10);
}
```

A call to `f` now returns immediately and the function prints and sleeps
in the dedicated thread.

NOTE: There is only one such thread and the call above will block all
other delegated functions for 10 seconds.

fix reading of id3v2 tags at the end of files

Interesting bug! With gcc on my system (amd64), this is false
(which causes a wrong seek in id3.c):

int foo(uint32_t x) {
    return ((off_t) (-x)) == ((off_t) (-((off_t) x)));
}

It might be different for other compilers (e.g. tcc is fine for me) or
on 32-bit platforms.

configure: add -Wformat-security to gcc options

Ubuntu enables this by default and it is useful to detect possible
security problems. -Wformat-nonliteral on the other hand is to strict,
because it doesn't even allow:

const char *fmt = "%d\n";
printf(fmt, i);
